\section*{Bolus doses and drug calculations of time}

Sometimes we have to give bolus doses, or a oneoff dose. We need to calculate this and very often these doses cannot be given in an instant, such as swallowing a tablet, and must be infused over a period of time.

Here is an example to illustrate this point:
Your patient requires a bolus dose of 2 g of medication. You have 500 mg in 5 ml solution for
injection available. The drug can be given at a rate of 1 ml every minute.

First we calculate the dose and we start with our unit conversion.
$$\begin{gathered}
2 \times 1000=2000 \mathrm{mg} \\
2000 / 500 \times 5=20 \mathrm{ml}
\end{gathered}$$

So we know we need to give 20 ml and we can do so at a rate of 1 ml every minute:
$$20 \times 1=20 \text { minutes. }$$

That was quite simple so let's look at another example.

Your patient requires a bolus dose of 1.2 g of medication. You have 300 mg in 5 ml solution for injection available. The drug can be given at a rate of 1 ml every 30 seconds.

First we calculate the dose and we start with our unit conversion:
$$\begin{aligned}
& 1.2 \times 1000=1200 \mathrm{mg} \\
& 1200 / 300 \times 5=20 \mathrm{ml}
\end{aligned}$$

So we know we need to give 20 ml and we can do so at a rate of 1 ml every 30 seconds:
$$20 \times 30=600 \text { seconds }$$

To convert this to minutes we need to divide by the number of seconds in a minute, so:
$$600 / 60=10 \text { minutes to give the dose. }$$

Shall we do one more?
Your patient requires a bolus dose of 3.6 g of medication. You have 600 mg in 2 ml solution for injection available. The drug can be given at a rate of 1 ml every 15 seconds.

First we calculate the dose and we start with our unit conversion:
$$\begin{aligned}
& 3.6 \times 1000=3600 \mathrm{mg} \\
& 3600 / 600 \times 2=12 \mathrm{ml}
\end{aligned}$$

So we know we need to give 12 ml and we can do so at a rate of 1 ml every 15 seconds.
$$12 \times 15=180 \text { seconds }$$

To convert this to minutes we need to divide by the number of seconds in a minute so:
$$180 / 60=3 \text { minutes to give the dose. }$$

I hope these examples have helped you to see and understand the processes in bolus dose calculations over time.

\section*{Drug calculations by weight}

Some medications require us to calculate the dose based on a patients weight. These drugs are prescribed on a mg per kg basis and therefore we must obtain the patients weight in kg in an accurate manner. Many of these calculations are for medication for children and it is essential we get doses correct as errors can lead to overdose and complications.

Here is an example to illustrate the point:
Your patient requires their medicine at a dose of $60 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg} /$ day (milligrams per kilogram per day). They weigh 12 kg .

So the calculation will look like this:
$$60 \times 12=720 \mathrm{mg} \text { per day. }$$

This may be a one off dose or it may be required to be split. In this case we want to give it in 4 divided doses, so:
$$720 / 4=180 \mathrm{mg} \text { per dose }$$

Can you see how that worked? Let's do another.
Your patient requires their medicine at a dose of $30 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg} / \mathrm{day}$. They weigh 15 kg . The dose must be given in 3 divided doses.

So the calculation will look like this:
$$\begin{aligned}
& 30 \times 15=450 \mathrm{mg} \text { per day } \\
& 450 / 3=150 \mathrm{mg} \text { per dose }
\end{aligned}$$

That is the basis of weight calculations. Sometimes these are in children and often that means a liquid dose calculation too, so let's do all of the steps.

Your patient requires their medicine at a dose of $50 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg} / \mathrm{day}$. They weigh 20 kg . The drug must be given in 4 divided doses and you have a liquid available that is 125 mg in 5 ml .

So the calculation will look like this:
$$\begin{gathered}
50 \times 20=1000 \mathrm{mg} \text { per day } \\
1000 / 4=250 \mathrm{mg} \text { per dose } \\
250 / 125 \times 5=10 \mathrm{ml} \text { per dose }
\end{gathered}$$

I hope that makes weight calculations clear for you.

