\section*{Monoamine oxidase inhibitors}

Monoamine oxidase (MAO) exists in two forms, MAO-A and MAO-B, and both are responsible for chemically breaking down monoamines to render them inactive. MAOIs block this breakdown, and phenalzine is an example. The blocking leads to an increase in the availability of the monoamines which, as with TCAs, leads to an antidepressant effect.

These drugs are used infrequently due to their high risk of drug interactions, especially with other antidepressants. They are also able to interact negatively with some foodstuffs containing
tyramine and dopamine (e.g. some cheeses, red wine, pickled herring and others). This interaction can cause blood pressure to increase to a dangerous level and patients on these medications are warned to avoid these foods.

MAOIS bind irreversibly but there is a reversible MAOI, moclobemide, which is also used.

